## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2015 Anthem Health Insurance breach** — at the time one of the largest healthcare data breaches in US history, affecting nearly 79 million people. What stood out to me was not just the scale but the breakdown that made it possible.

Anthem had compliance programs in place. They were a large, well-resourced organization. But investigators found that the breach exploited gaps between their governance, risk, and compliance functions — specifically that their risk assessments had not kept pace with their actual threat environment, and that leadership had not prioritized the technical controls that would have limited the damage.

What I took from that: compliance alone did not save them. Having policies on paper did not save them. The missing piece was an integrated GRC approach where risk findings actually drove governance decisions, and compliance was the result of genuinely good security — not just documentation.

The question I kept thinking about after reading this was: *what does it actually take to make these three things talk to each other in a real organization?* I do not have a complete answer yet, but I think asking that question is the right way to approach the rest of this project.

